Pour @cold salted water{300%ml} into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting lid.
Stir in the @rice{150%g} then bring to the boil.
Once boiling, lower the heat to medium and cover with the lid.
Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the #pot{} from the heat.
Keep covered for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will
continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic
press{}).
Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.
Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{1}(thinly sliced).

Drain the @tofu{180%g}, pat dry with #kitchen paper{} and coarsely grate.
Place a pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.
When hot, fry the tofu with garlic, @ground cumin{1%sachet}, @Mexican style
spice mix{2%sachets} and @salt{1/2%tsp}, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Pour in the @chopped tomato with onion & garlic{1%pack}, beans, @vegetable
stock{1%sachet}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @chipotle dried chilli flakes{1%sachet}.
Cover and cook for ~{6-8%minutes}.

Once cooked, add the @peas{120%g} and @chipotle paste{1%sachet} and cook,
stirring, until the peas have warmed through, ~{1%minute}.
Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Loosen the stew
with a splash of @water{to taste} if you feel it's too thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between #bowls{}.
Top the rice with spoonfuls of tofu and bean chilli.
Finish with a sprinkling of scallion.

> As the name suggests, this is a meat-free take on the type of beef mince
> chillis typically favoured in firehouses across the US. Sitting on a bed of
> fluffy rice, this dish features tofu and an expert mix of spices.